"If I think back to my secondary school days when staff looked like they had just walked off the set of Life on Mars, there was something of a revolution afoot in state secondary school education in England. Our teachers, many of whom were students in the 1960s, tried to engage us in our learning. They had us drawing pictures and writing stories and even doing drama. They tried just about anything to move away from the idea that education happens when an older, authoritarian figure stands in front of a row of desks and tells those sitting upright and attentive what they need to know. I did my teacher training in the second half of the 1980s, by which time we were trying to learn the lessons of that revolution. We realised that we had to use the tools of innovation, while keeping the core ideas such as spelling and reasonable grammar."
